PdM is a key component of Industry 4.0, which has helped in combining AI, IoT, and advanced analytics and further advancement of equipment reliability, reduce downtime. Recent work points towards the growing adoption of ML and DL promising techniques for fault diagnosis and remaining useful life prediction in industrial workflows. A bibliometric analysis in AI-driven predictive maintenance shows a trend of increase in publications focusing more and more on data-driven approaches, hybrid AI models, and real-time monitoring workflows. The study  emphasized the importance of trust, transparency, and ethical considerations in AI-enabled maintenance systems.
In IOT-4, PdM frameworks which is backed by AI was majorly trained on multi-sensor data, side by side using these vibration, temperature, force, and acoustic signals, to monitor equipment health. Hybrid deep learning architectures, one being CNNs conjoined with LSTM networks, have shown groundbreaking capability of identifying spatial and temporal patterns from sensor streams, gaining high prediction accuracy. Moreover, IOT sensor fusion, edge computing, and cloud-based monitoring have improved the real-time decision-making and predictive capabilities.
Even though there exist these advancements,there are also limitations. Although the previous studies in the field had there complete focus on accuracy and algorithm, but there are challenges of noisy high-dimensional sensor data, model generalization, and scalable deployment which were not given attention. Moreover, major research work was done on AI without data science analytics, sensor fusion, and  maintenance decision support into a collective framework.
To overcome the gaps preset in the industry, the study directs towards an AI-based predictive maintenance framework in robots which ensures to bring together the multi-sensor analytics, ML based fault prediction, and data science promising  techniques. Unlike the previous work-done in this field, our work tries to demonstrate the use of sensor fusion and predictive analytics in robots to improve accurate and real-time decisions in manufacturing environments.
